    <h1 id="spaces">Spaces</h1>
    <h2>How to input Spaces in your ReturnSuite model</h2>
    <br>
    <p>
      Within ReturnSuite, the concept of Spaces is used to define the different
      physical areas of a property. You can define Spaces in any way you
      wish–by unit, floor, building, lot, etc. For example, you may want to
      define an office property’s Spaces by floor, multi-tenant warehouse by
      unit and a suburban office campus by building.
    </p>
    <p>
      As a general guide, you’re probably initially best served by dividing
      your property into Spaces that have some combination of different
      physical characteristics which are unlikely to change over your
      Analysis Period.
    </p>
    <p>
      For example in a mixed use building that is a mall on the ground floor
      and a mix of residential and office in a tower above, you may want to
      divide your property into the following Spaces:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          For the mall area, the Spaces could be blocks of units divided by
          the concourses, since you’re unlikely to change the mall layout. You
          may also want to specifically separate out Spaces in the food court
          or identify units that have a combination of exterior and interior
          entrances.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          For the residential portion of the tower, you may want to define the
          entire residential portion as a single Space since the units are
          relatively homogeneous in terms of physical attributes and revenue
          and costs on a per-area basis.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          For the office portion of the tower, you may want to define each
          floor or even each suite as a Space.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Alternatively, if you were modeling a small residential property with
      four rental units, you may want to define each unit as its own Space.
    </p>
