    <h3>Entering in Space details:</h3>
    <h4>Space Name</h4>
    <p>
      Input a name for the Space, for example Suite 201, 3rd Floor or
      Building C. ReturnSuite is designed to be ‘Multiplayer’, so use a name
      that others on your team will understand and ideally corresponds to
      either the leases or Space Use.
    </p>
    <h4>Gross Leasable Area</h4>
    <p>
      Input the size of the Space. Expenses and expense recoveries often
      use this information, so even the lease is a flat amount that isn’t
      linked to the size of the Space, it’s a good idea to input an accurate
      Gross Leasable Area.
    </p>
    <h4>Availability Scope</h4>
    <p>
      Over time, it is not uncommon for the physical layout of properties to
      adapt to meet the needs of new tenants and uses. Sometimes these
      physical changes result in decreases or increases to the Gross
      Leasable Area of a property. In other cases Spaces are either
      combined or be further split into more Spaces.
    </p>
    <p>
      To accommodate the changes to Spaces over time, ReturnSuite has the Scope
      function. There are four Scope options available:
    </p>
    <dl>
      <dt>
        <span>Always present</span>
        <span>(default)</span>
      </dt>
      <dd>
        The Space exists and will exist for the duration of the Analysis Period.
        This will be the case for the vast majority of use cases within
        ReturnSuite.
      </dd>
      <dt>Until date</dt>
      <dd>
        The Space exists in the beginning of the Analysis Period, but it will
        cease to exist at a specific point in time during the Analysis Period.
        <br>
        For example, if your property consisted of five 20,000 sf warehouses
        and one of the warehouses was going to be demolished on May 1, 2028,
        thereby decreasing the total Gross Leasable Area from 100,000 sf to
        80,000 sf. You would use the Until Date option and select a date of
        May 1, 2028.
      </dd>
      <dt>After date</dt>
      <dd>
        The Space does not exist at the beginning of the Analysis Period, but
        it will come into existence at a specific point in time during the
        Analysis Period.
        <br>
        For example, if you were going to add three additional floors to an
        office property which were scheduled to become online as of November
        15th, 2029. You would use the After Date option and select a date of
        November 15th, 2029.
      </dd>
      <dt>Date range</dt>
      <dd>
        The Space does not exist at either the beginning or the end of the
        Analysis Period, but it will come into existence during the Analysis
        Period.
        <br>
        For example, if you were going to add a temporary structure to your
        property for June through to August 2025, you would use the Date Range
        option and select a starting date of June 1st, 2025 and an end date of
        August 30, 2025.
      </dd>
    </dl>
    <h4>Replacement Leasing Rules</h4>
    <p>
      For each Space, you can select from the Replacement Leasing Rules you
      built in either the Market Parameters (Quick Start) or in the Replacement
      Leasing Rules under the Model menu.
    </p>
    <p>
      Another option available under Market Parameters is
      <b>Unavailable Going Forward</b>. This option holds the Space vacant. You
      may use this option in combination with Scope to account for major
      redevelopments. For example, say you plan to completely redevelop a
      property which has …
    </p>
    <p>
      The Replacement Leasing Rules will slot in theoretical future leases for
      any vacancies. If you do not add a Use, it will treat the Space as vacant
      and slot the first lease in using the Replacement Leasing Rules.
    </p>
